      nanos: 571617703
    }
  }
  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Pinpointing the Config**\n\nI\'ve zeroed in on the `vite.config.ts` file. It seems that `process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY` and `process.env.API_KEY` are being defined using a clever `define` configuration. Vite appears to be reading the `GEMINI_API_KEY` directly from the environment, thanks to the `loadEnv` function. It seems like the keys are loaded at build time.\n\n\n**Analyzing the Exposure**\n\nI\'ve realized the current setup, while not hardcoding, still exposes the API key to the client. Vite\'s `define` config embeds it during build time, defeating the purpose of environment variables. The question is explicitly answered now, but I must explore full-stack refactoring to truly protect the key. The API key *is* exposed at build time, and thus to client, and a full-stack restructuring is required to hide it again.\n\n\n**Addressing the Vulnerability**\n\nI\'m now formulating my response. There\'s no hardcoded key in the repo. The app checks `process.env.API_KEY` or `process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY` in `/services/geminiService.ts`. These environment variables are loaded by `loadEnv` in `/vite.config.ts`, but this leads to client-side exposure. I\'ll highlight the security flaw and offer a full-stack restructuring solution.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "Based on the codebase, there is **no hardcoded API key** in your source files. Here is exactly how it is currently being pulled:\n\n1. **Service Layer (`/services/geminiService.ts`)**: \n   The code tries to access the key using `process.env.API_KEY` or `process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY`. \n   \n2. **Build Configuration (`/vite.config.ts`)**: \n   Since this is a React frontend application, `process.env` wouldn\'t normally work in the browser. However, your Vite configuration uses `loadEnv()` to read the `GEMINI_API_KEY` from the system\'s environment variables and explicitly injects it into your frontend code during the build process using Vite\'s `define` property.\n\n### \342\232\240\357\270\217 Important Security Note\nBecause of this current setup, your Gemini API key is currently being **exposed directly to the browser\'s client-side code** when the app is built and served. \n\nWould you like me to restructure the app into a full-stack application (adding a lightweight Express server) to proxy these AI requests? That is the recommended approach to ensure your API key remains hidden and secure entirely on the back end!"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 4
      nanos: 355001296
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
